<p>Apparently I read about 80 books this year, not even accounting for the four epic poems I read twice: the <cite>Iliad</cite>, the <cite>Odyssey</cite>, <cite>Beowulf</cite>, and Dave Jilk's <cite>Epoch</cite>. Highlights were the plays of Shakespeare, George Eliot's magisterial novel <cite>Middlemarch</cite>, <cite>Bach and the Patterns of Invention</cite> by Laurence Dreyfus, an intensive re-reading of Aristotle's <cite>Nicomachean Ethics</cite>, and the aforementioned epic poems. For 2025 I plan to immerse myself further in the world of epic poems, explore more novels of the Bildungsroman variety, complete intensive re-readings of Aristotle's lesser-known <cite>Eudemian Ethics</cite> and <cite>Great Ethics</cite>, and maybe try to tackle <cite>Moby-Dick</cite>.</p>
